column10: Its a game i have been wanting to get so i would recommend to other players

Garry's Mod is a great and fun sandbox game where you can do whatever you want. However, the reason why i'm not recommending this game in this state is because of the two controversy updates:
https://www.reddit.com/r/Games/comments/bjio60/garrys_mod_april_30th_update_introduces/?rdt=64514
https://www.reddit.com/r/pcgaming/comments/mnia4b/defining_server_operator_rules_garrys_mod/

When the April 2019 Update came out, it added Gameanalytics where they include a Terrible EULA, Shady Analytics, and they can even monitor your chat and ban if you say a no-no word. Once it got added, our Freedom got limited by Facepuch because they don't really care about the Playerbase anymore.

Even worse, on April 2021, they added Server Operator Rules to police around servers and use blanket bans if there's content they don't like on them. Why would Facepunch need to add these BOTH Gameanalytics & Server Operator Rules? It should be up to the Server Owners/Admins to allow which content they allow and what people can say on their servers INSTEAD of Blanket Bans, BOTH the Gameanalytics & Server Operator Rules has NO reason to exist.

This will be the Dark Future of Gmod whatever we like it or not. UNLESS, we fight it.

For the Gmod Community:
Please start a petition or something like that, forcing Facepunch to REMOVE both Gameanalytics & Server Operator Rules and become transparent again like they did before the April 2019 Update. So that means, no EULA, no Analytics, no Blanket Bans, OR any changes that has been made from the Gameanalytics OR Server Operator Rules. Because remember, Sandbox games are supposed to be to quote from the Minecraft 2011 Trailer: "No one can tell you what you can or cannot do, with no rules to follow."

And once both Gameanalytics & Server Operator Rules gets removed, i'll install and play Gmod again and even give it a positive review. But until then, I can only hope for the best...

This is game is an all time classic for the Steam community,
Developed by Facepunch, Published by valve.

Gmod (Garry's Mod) was so perfect down to the very last detail, but of course everything must come to an end and unfortunately for this game it is that time. It's not as popular or thriving like how it used to be years ago but it was definitely the "Golden" era of its time (Definitely mine).

Back in 2015 I remember downloading this game and hopping on it for the first time, there I met friends along each server I visited and every time it never felt like it failed to feel like I had a purpose there. God the memories I had with the ones who stood by me were endless, I played most of the game modes but DarkRP has to be my most time all favorite. I played on a server named MonolithRP, a hyper realistic server with gameplay very different from the other DarkRP. There I made so many memories with the community, it felt like a home almost and its very sad to see it fade away.

This game is very fun to play in 2024 and I highly recommend anyone who hasn't tried it to give it a shot, whether its with downloading a bunch of mods and messing around with friends in sandbox or if your looking for more of a life style progressive story then DarkRP is a place for you, most servers are decent with very well made detail and some are just not for others. 

But don't let me explain it for you. Play It Yourself.

Close enough. Walt rises without waking his wife. He exits.

Garry's Mod is not just a game, it's a playground for creativity and imagination. You can do anything you want in this sandbox, from building your own contraptions, vehicles, and weapons, to exploring thousands of user-made maps, modes, and addons. The possibilities are endless, and the fun never stops.

I love how Garry's Mod lets me express myself and interact with other players online. I can join servers that host different games, such as Trouble in Terrorist Town, Prop Hunt, Murder, DarkRP, and more. I can also download and install addons that add new content, such as models, textures, sounds, and scripts. Some of my favourite addons are Wiremod, PAC3, and Cinema.

Garry's Mod is a game that never gets old, because there is always something new to discover and enjoy. It is a game that challenges me to be creative and innovative, and rewards me with satisfaction and amusement. It is a game that I would recommend to anyone who loves gaming and having fun.

Animations, artwork, contraptions, game modes, and just general tomfoolery all packaged into one amazing game. Want to make some funny videos with rag-dolls and props, take an amazing screenshot of a diorama you made, drive around in a bunch of vehicles, build some structures, role-play, or just simply mess around? Garry's Mod has you covered! With over 22.8k hours into this game from years ago as of writing this review, I'd say it's worth it despite its age and technical limitations. Also the flexibility of this game in terms of its physics engine as well as compatibility capability is truly amazing considering the game engine it was made in as well as for the time when it first released, even if it isn't perfect. The game also has quite a cultural significance and legacy too with Garry's Mod animations and content still being made to this day as of writing this. I'd recommend this game to anyone willing to give it a try if you have the hardware space for the addons that you'll install over time.

TLDR: Funny sandbox game with great flexibility for doing whatever you want with it.

Garry's Mod has a ton of random things to do, yet it doesn't feel that fun after awhile, I never find my self playing this game for more than a hour. If you have a ton of people to play with the game can be fun for a long time, but with only around 4 people it gets boring quick, there isn't a ton of good mods mostly just dumb joke mods that don't even function, and overall it just feels, empty, like there's a void in the game that cannot be filled, if that makes sense. I give this game a tough time but if your creative you can definitely make it fun, and certain servers like fudgy's can be pretty fun too, if there isn't a ton of annoying people, and for only $10 or $5 when it's on sale, it really isn't that bad, but for the average person it really isn't a game your gonna be on all the time. I recommend that you buy this game because it is really fun for the first few weeks, and if a thing like covid ever happens again, then you'll have something to do all the time, all in all, this is a pretty good game.

Garry's Mod, affectionately known as GMod, is a digital wonderland that transcends traditional gaming boundaries. Developed by Facepunch Studios and originally released in 2004, this game has stood the test of time and continues to captivate players with its limitless potential for creativity and sheer entertainment value.

At its core, Garry's Mod is a sandbox game that places the power of creation firmly in the hands of its players. The premise is deceptively simple: you're dropped into a virtual world with a wide array of tools, props, and models, and from there, the possibilities become almost boundless. Want to build a towering skyscraper? You can. Dreaming of staging an epic battle between superheroes and zombies? GMod lets you do it. The game's flexibility and openness foster an environment where creativity knows no bounds.

One of Garry's Mod's greatest strengths lies in its modding community, which has flourished over the years. The Steam Workshop is a treasure trove of user-created content, ranging from new game modes and maps to intricate models and textures. The diversity of available mods ensures that every play session can be a unique experience. Whether you're exploring a haunted mansion, participating in a thrilling car race, or engaging in a hilarious game of Prop Hunt with friends, GMod always has something new to offer.

The multiplayer aspect of Garry's Mod is where the game truly shines. The ability to join servers with custom game modes and unique modifications transforms GMod into an ever-evolving social experience. From the chaotic joy of Trouble in Terrorist Town to the cooperative challenge of GMod Tower, the multiplayer component adds layers of depth and excitement that keep players coming back for more.

Furthermore, Garry's Mod has become a breeding ground for content creators. YouTube and Twitch are filled with hilarious and creative videos featuring GMod gameplay. The game's propensity for unexpected and absurd moments ensures that each session is a potential goldmine of entertaining content.

It's worth noting that the game's graphics may not be cutting-edge by today's standards, but its charm lies in its simplicity. The intentionally basic visuals serve as a canvas upon which players can project their imagination without the distraction of flashy graphics. The low system requirements also make Garry's Mod accessible to a broad audience, ensuring that anyone with a computer can join in on the fun.

In conclusion, Garry's Mod is more than just a game; it's a platform for limitless creativity, social interaction, and unbridled fun. Its enduring popularity is a testament to its unique appeal and the dedicated community that continues to breathe new life into it. Whether you're a seasoned veteran or a newcomer exploring its vast possibilities, Garry's Mod remains a timeless masterpiece in the world of gaming.

Cheesecake recipe

Ingredients
Ingredient Checklist
Crust:
1 ½ cups graham cracker crumbs
¼ teaspoon ground cinnamon
⅓ cup unsalted butter or margarine, melted
FILLING:
4 (8 oz.) packages cream cheese, softened
1 ¼ cups sugar
½ cup sour cream
2 teaspoons vanilla extract
5 large eggs
TOPPING:
½ cup sour cream
2 teaspoons sugar

DirectionsInstructions Checklist
Step 1
Preheat oven to 475°F. Place a large pan filled with 1/2 inch water in oven.

Step 2
Make crust: Mix graham cracker crumbs and cinnamon; add butter or margarine. Press crust onto bottom and 2/3 of the way up a 9-inch springform pan lined with parchment. Wrap a large piece of foil around bottom of pan. Freeze until filling is prepared.

Step 3
Make filling: Use an electric mixer to mix cream cheese, sugar, sour cream and vanilla. Blend until smooth and creamy. Scrape down sides of bowl. Whisk eggs in a bowl; add to cream cheese mixture. Blend just until eggs are incorporated.

Step 4
Remove crust from freezer and pour in filling. Carefully place cheesecake into preheated water bath. Bake for 12 minutes; turn oven to 350°F and bake until top of cheesecake turns golden, 50 to 60 minutes. Remove cake to a wire rack to cool.

Step 5
Make topping: Combine sour cream and sugar; spread over cake. Cover and refrigerate at least 4 hours.

Edit:

So I started playing this game in 2020. I was a toddler and I am still a toddler now. I played it on my dad's PC and just had fun messing around with stuff. I really do enjoy playing this game but there are a lot of negative things about this game.

1. Multiplayer. The multiplayer in this game can be fun especially when you play with people around your age (mentally or physically) but there are a lot of problems there. One is the abusing admins. I got random killed by some admin for no reason. Even if I respawned, they kept attacking me so I couldn't do anything in that server. I left and went to other sandbox servers. Generally, they were fun. I could play with kids around my age and some adults too. I enjoyed most of them (probably because I was lucky and also that I was young) but still, I did play on terrible servers. Two is the weird servers. I only heard about them so I'm pretty much just blind firing right now but some servers are just bad even without people in them. Raping, school shooting, Nazi, you name it. DarkRP servers are pretty much just memes now. Sandbox is full of mods to the point it takes hours just to load in.

2. Mods. Mods and sandbox is pretty much the only two reasons I ever asked my dad to buy this game. It makes the community creative and diverse with content. That's why garrysmod.org, Mod DB, GameBanana, and other modding sites existed. That's why enjoyed this game. But a lot of these mods and mod creators are bad sometimes. Sex/hentai mods, server content mods, weapon mods, playermodel mods, etc. Some of these mods are just degenerate stuff. And let me tell you as an porn addict: they're awful. They fry your goddamn brain like nothing. Using those sex and hentai garbage is like burning your fucking brain with a flamethrower directly while you're still alive. Don't be a degenerate installing those mods, you will regret it.

3. Gmod Realism. I'm not telling you to stop making or liking Gmod realism videos. In fact, I do watch them too. Gmod realism videos are so unoriginal because the videos are almost identical to each other. They use the same weapons, same playermodels, same maps, same graphic, same HUDs, same fucking everything. They're the same shit, different video. Some realism videos are just horrible even if they're "original" Like those school shooter or terrorist realism videos. They're disgusting.

I really like this game. It's fun and it was the reason I started playing PC games on Steam. You may say the community completely ruined the mod. And that may be true. But I will never stop playing it. I still enjoy it even with all its issues. But I recommend staying away from multiplayer unless you play with your friends or trusted people. In the end, it's good, and bad.

Rating: ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

Review:

Garry's Mod, affectionately known as GMod, is a masterpiece of sandbox gaming that continues to captivate players with its boundless creativity and endless possibilities. As a longtime fan of the game, I can confidently say that GMod stands as a shining beacon in the world of gaming, offering an experience unlike any other.

At its core, GMod provides players with a blank canvas upon which they can unleash their imagination. Whether you're building intricate structures, scripting complex contraptions, or simply goofing around with friends, the only limit in GMod is your own creativity. From towering skyscrapers to fantastical worlds and everything in between, the freedom to create is truly awe-inspiring.

One of the defining features of GMod is its vast array of user-generated content. With thousands of player-made addons, mods, and game modes available through the Steam Workshop, the possibilities for customization are virtually endless. Whether you're adding new weapons and vehicles, introducing unique gameplay mechanics, or crafting entirely new experiences, the community-driven nature of GMod ensures that there's always something new to discover.

The multiplayer aspect of GMod is where the game truly shines. Whether you're teaming up with friends to tackle cooperative challenges, engaging in intense PvP battles, or simply hanging out in a virtual sandbox, the social aspect of GMod adds a layer of depth and excitement to the experience. The sense of camaraderie and collaboration within the GMod community is truly remarkable, fostering a welcoming and inclusive environment for players of all ages and skill levels.

Despite its seemingly simplistic graphics and gameplay mechanics, GMod boasts surprising depth and complexity. The Source engine provides a solid foundation for physics-based gameplay, allowing for realistic interactions and dynamic environments. Whether you're building elaborate Rube Goldberg machines, constructing intricate puzzles, or staging epic battles, the physics engine adds a level of realism and immersion that is both impressive and entertaining.

In conclusion, Garry's Mod is a testament to the power of creativity and community in gaming. With its limitless possibilities, vibrant modding scene, and welcoming community, GMod continues to stand the test of time as a true classic in the world of sandbox gaming. Whether you're a seasoned veteran or a newcomer eager to explore the wonders of GMod for the first time, one thing is certain: in Garry's Mod, the only limit is your imagination.

I am 3 years old.

My ex-wife and I have a daughter together, and we adopted our son together. Both are now 20 years old.

When we were going through our separation, I felt lost and unhappy. I was self-destructive. One day, I was so angry with everything spiraling out of control that I punched a concrete wall in a moment of overwhelming emotion. This resulted in breaking my fifth metacarpal in my right hand—the hand I worked with, played games with, and used to carry my children to bed—the hand I desperately needed to ensure I could continue providing.

Upon learning the severity of the self-inflicted damage, I became almost suicidal. Keep in mind that just a few months before this, I was the happiest man, with no history of depression or anxiety. I had never experienced anger outbursts, nor was I the type to break down and cry, but I was in a tough situation that truly prevented me from seeing the light on the other side.

With nothing better to do, I looked for a game I could play WITH ONE HAND while recovering. Somehow, I stumbled upon this game and read some of the comments. I decided it was worth a try... I must admit I didn't beat the game, nor did I play as much as some of you. In fact, I may have played this game for only a day or two. That being said, after doing so, I had a new joy and hope for life. I managed to leave behind the pain and suffering that had been thrust upon me. I could experience the joy and happiness of other people. I relaxed for 5 ♥♥♥♥ minutes listening to this music, long enough to realize that I would be okay.

After realizing this, I turned off the game and went back to work. My hand hurt a lot, but I was motivated. I stopped feeling so sorry for myself and became the father I needed to be at that moment, not the weak boy I was behaving like.

Today, I am close friends with the mother of my children. We don't fight, argue, or say hurtful things to each other. We are parents and friends.

Now I have 3 children. My third child is, wait, ALSO 20 YEARS OLD. The woman I am with was going through a very similar situation at the time of my separation, and we just unexpectedly stumbled into each other's lives. We have been dating for a year and are very happy together.

Moral of the story: you never know what life has in store for you, and if I had given up when all odds were against me, I wouldn't be where I am today. This silly little game helped me realize that.

Please give me an award.
thank you.

I went to eat at my favorite restaurant the other day. You know what I ordered? I got a mouth watering hamburger. I waited 20 minutes for it to arrive and they gave me only the damn buns.
I asked them, "What the hell?!"
The waiter responds calmly, "Sir, you must wait the rest of the burger to arrive."
I told him in a annoyed tone, "Fine."
As the evening progressed, I kept getting bits and pieces of the burger. First the lettuce. Then the cheese. Once the patty finally came, they started taking parts like the cheese and the top bun from me.
I ask the waiter in a pissed tone, "What the ♥♥♥♥! Where are my top bun and cheese going?"
He told me, "Since your plate lacks sufficient room and you are no longer enjoying them, we are removing them from your plate."
Now, I'm stuck here with parts of a burger and throughout my service I get different types of the same toppings. First it was romaine lettuce, then it was iceberg. I get basic white bread buns. Now, I have brioche. I have lost all sense of time and understanding of what my meal should look like. Garry's Mod isn't just a game; it's a canvas for your imagination, a playground where the only limit is your creativity. Developed by Facepunch Studios, this sandbox phenomenon invites players to explore, create, and share their wildest creations in a world of endless possibilities.

Whether you're building towering structures with physics-based props, crafting intricate vehicles and contraptions, or staging epic battles with friends, Garry's Mod offers an unparalleled sandbox experience that's as limitless as your imagination.

With its vast array of user-generated content, from custom game modes to player-created mods and addons, the game's community ensures that there's always something new and exciting to discover. So whether you're a seasoned veteran or a newcomer to the world of Garry's Mod, dive in, let your imagination run wild, and prepare to be amazed.

My son got this game for Christmas in 2020 from his uncle, so we installed it on his computer and he started playing. By the end of the week he had 24 hours on this game. This was horrible for me, as it was already hard for me to find ways to spend time with my son, as he is always out with his friends or just watching YouTube. I loved it as it was the best time I had spent with my Son since my wife had died. This game has ever since brought me and my son closer again and now we actually spend time together outside the house together as well. This game reminded me that there's fun to be had in everything, and it has brought both me and my Son many happy memories.

(LONG VER):
While it's certainly possible to write a text outlining potential downsides of Garry's Mod, it wouldn't be entirely objective or representative of the game's overall experience. It's important to address both sides of the argument and offer a balanced perspective. So, instead of focusing solely on negativity, let's explore some potential shortcomings alongside the aspects that contribute to its long-standing success:

Potential Downsides:

Steep Learning Curve: Garry's Mod (GMod) is a sandbox with immense depth and possibilities. This freedom comes at the cost of an initial learning curve. Understanding the nuances of physics, scripting, and mods can be overwhelming for newcomers. Without guidance or community support, initial frustration is understandable.

Reliance on Community Content: While the core GMod experience offers basic tools, the true potential lies in community-created content. This means relying on external mods, maps, and gamemodes, which can vary in quality and stability. Finding high-quality content may require effort and experimentation.

Performance Issues: Due to its open-ended nature and reliance on user-generated content, GMod can be susceptible to performance problems, especially on lower-end machines. Complex creations or poorly optimized servers can lead to lag and frame drops.

Toxic Player Communities: Like any online game, GMod's multiplayer scene can attract negative elements. Some servers harbor toxic behavior, griefing, and trolling. Finding the right community requires discernment and filtering through options.

Monetary Investment: While the base game is relatively inexpensive, the true potential emerges with paid mods and tools. This can add up for players interested in specific features or experiences.

Limited Single-Player Experience: While single-player options exist, GMod shines in its multiplayer and collaborative aspects. Players seeking a purely story-driven or solo experience might find GMod lacking.

Outdated Graphics: Released in 2004, GMod's visuals haven't aged as gracefully as other titles. Players prioritizing cutting-edge graphics might not be impressed.

It's Important to Consider:

Immense Creativity and Replayability: Despite the learning curve, GMod empowers players to create virtually anything they can imagine. Building contraptions, roleplaying scenarios, and participating in diverse gamemodes offer near-limitless replayability.

Active and Supportive Community: The GMod community is renowned for its helpfulness and creativity. Numerous guides, tutorials, and active forums assist players in overcoming challenges and unlocking the game's potential.

Regular Updates and Content: Over its long lifespan, GMod has received consistent updates and improvements. The influx of community-created content ensures constant evolution and fresh experiences.

Wide Range of Experiences: Unlike many games with predefined goals, GMod caters to diverse preferences. Whether it's collaborative building, competitive gamemodes, story-driven roleplay, or just messing around, the possibilities are vast.

Accessibility and Affordability: Compared to graphically demanding titles, GMod requires relatively modest hardware, making it accessible to a broader audience. The base game price remains reasonable, with additional content optional.

Conclusion:

Garry's Mod isn't perfect, and its unique nature presents certain challenges. However, focusing solely on negatives disregards its immense strengths and the dedicated community that sustains it. The learning curve can be overcome, and the investment of time and effort yields a sandbox brimming with creativity, replayability, and diverse experiences. Whether its shortcomings outweigh its merits depends entirely on individual preferences and expectations. It's crucial to consider both sides before forming an informed opinion.

One of, if not THE oldest popular sandbox experience compared to other mainstream titles.

[h1]GAMEPLAY[/h1]
The base game alone has plenty of tools and assets to toy around with and create all sorts of things. But where this game really shines is the Steam Workshop. Where users come together to create and share addons for the game. From original content, to ports from other games, it's safe to say the workshop is a promising place with a indefinite amount of content in store.

The game also comes bundled with two gamemodes by default, being Sandbox and Trouble in Terrorist Town (TTT). The latter of which is a murder mystery gamemode with all sorts of features and tools to play around with round-to-round.

[h1]MULTIPLAYER[/h1]
Co-op with others in this game can be memorable for either for the right or wrong reasons. Dedicated servers can be fun from time to time (as long as you don't run into any unsavory individuals), but I'd argue gmod's full fun-tential comes from having a squad of friends on speed dial for peer-to-peer sessions.

[h1]CONCLUSION[/h1]
Overall, I would say it's the bestestest sandbox title evar, and I r8 it 11/10. Thanks for all the best friends Garry <3

Garry's mod is THE default sandbox of Steam having it as one of my first game and playing it on and off for the better part of a decade and also not playing and enjoying Steam VR. Made my own collection of mods me and my friends use to play, and just love the community around the game even if that community around the game can be quite problematic...odd...

You can literally do pretty much anything in the game to your hearts desire given the amount of content to this day that people keep making for the workshop.

Though the game is wide spread and amazing the only complaint I have with it is the lacking Linux support. While I use Windows 10 and don't run into these problems my friend who uses a steam deck keeps on crashing when he is using lots of addons as we do but I can confirm the list of addons I use while incredibly lengthy was tested to work fine with each other for the most part with no critical failure.

So my biggest complaint for the game is Proton and Linux need to be more supported as in its current state such things struggle if not outright fail to run the game with either if you go beyond a modest amount of addons. As such I have to give the game a 8/10 while it is the best game on Steam Sandbox wise that only applies if you have a Windows machine otherwise this game is off the table given the headache it creates for the other OSs...

If you are playing in VR I recommend this collection I made that can be found here https://steamcommunity.com/sharedfiles/filedetails/?id=2988328723 that comes with a nice QOL set of addons that keep the game vanilla but give players who are both in and out of VR a better vanilla experience.

As a devoted gamer, few titles have left an indelible mark on my gaming journey like Garry's Mod. The sheer awesomeness of this game lies in its ability to unlock the doors of creativity and immerse players in an ever-expanding universe of possibilities.

From the moment I stepped into the sandbox of GMod, I was immediately struck by the freedom it offered. The game serves as an open canvas, inviting me to shape and mold the virtual world according to my whims. The vast array of tools, props, and customizable options allowed me to construct intricate structures, design elaborate scenarios, and experiment with the game's physics engine in ways that constantly surprised and delighted me.

What sets Garry's Mod apart is its diverse and engaging game modes. I found myself seamlessly transitioning from intense rounds of Trouble in Terrorist Town, where trust is a rare commodity, to the imaginative chaos of Prop Hunt, where my friends and I would morph into everyday objects to evade detection. Each game mode felt like a unique adventure, ensuring that monotony had no place in my GMod experience.

The thriving modding community has been a constant source of inspiration. Exploring the Steam Workshop revealed an impressive collection of user-generated content, ranging from brilliantly designed maps to custom game modes that pushed the boundaries of what I thought was possible. The dedication and creativity of fellow players added layers of depth to Garry's Mod, turning it into a dynamic platform that evolves with the community's contributions.

What truly makes Garry's Mod awesome is the infectious humor and unpredictability that accompanies every session. The physics-based antics, whether it's launching ragdolls into the stratosphere or witnessing the hilarious mishaps during a custom game, never failed to elicit laughter. GMod, in essence, became my go-to source for genuine, unscripted gaming moments that left a lasting impact on my memories.

As I reflect on my time with Garry's Mod, it's evident that this game has achieved something special. Its timeless appeal, combined with a developer team committed to updates and improvements, ensures that the awesomeness persists. Garry's Mod isn't just a game; it's a celebration of creativity, community, and endless entertainment that has secured its place as a true gaming masterpiece.

[i]This is a review based on playing on the Steam Deck. I have yet to try it extensively on another device, so I may update my review once I give it a try on another system.[/i]

Okay, so I've been playing this title heavily since I got it a few days ago, and I already have some great things to say about it... as well as some not-so-great things.

First, let's talk about what the game truly is - it's a war simulation game turned sandbox environment. I'm not used to war games, as I typically stay clear from those games - titles like Call of Duty, DMZ Warzone, and even battle-royale games like Fortnite don't automatically appeal to me. I also don't usually go for sandbox games (I still am nauseated by seeing Minecraft everywhere). However, this game has caught my eye more than once, and I wondered what the hype has always been about ever since I first made my Steam account eight years ago. So, for New Year's 2024, I finally decided to join the hype train and got the game when it was on drastic sale.

[h1]The Good[/h1]
This is a nearly twenty year old game at this point, and it shows. It incorporates a lot of elements from the original Half-Life and Portal, and the 3D effects are somewhat rudimentary compared to modern titles with native ray-tracing effects and HDR support. However, that doesn't mean it isn't visually appealing, especially when you consider the various environments that have been designed just for this "game". There are many different maps to choose from, and almost every map is on the Steam Workshop.

Garry's Mod allows you to manipulate models, known as "ragdolls" in-game", to pose and express your creativity. The amount of options may seem daunting, at first, but once you mess around a little bit, you get to understand that each ragdoll has "bones", or rigid areas between point A and B (for instance, from the character's butt to the tip of its' tail, or from its' elbow to its' shoulder), which can be moved, resized, frozen in place, or made mobile using the "motor" property, to make the ragdoll do whatever you want it to. Garry's Mod is basically what Blender or Maya would look like if turned into a war game simulator.

You can also invoke several of these models into NPCs ("non-player characters"), in which they'll move around on their own. Typically, this is used in combat with each other - NPCs can either be allies to you ("friendly") or enemies ("hostile"). If you have elaborate scenes, any bullets, bombs, etc. can destroy them, so choose carefully!

The title's strength is in its' community-made mods on the Steam Workshop. There are hundreds of THOUSANDS of NPCs, weapons, items, maps, and various additional software to add on top of the already robust war simulator. Considering how many people already play this game, and due to how long it has been out here, it's really no wonder that there is so much. Pretty much, if you can think of a franchise - Looney Tunes, DC Comics, Marvel Comics, Animal Crossing, [i]waaaay[/i] too much Five Nights at Freddy's, and even VeggieTales - it has been ported to this game.

[h1]The Bad[/h1]
Now, my gripes. Basically, be careful what you import from the Workshop. Here are three things that I've experienced that you need to be aware of:

[b]Mod bugs and conflicts.[/b] When you download mods, always pay attention to the errors. I haven't, and my game crashes. [i]A lot.[/i] Now, it could be that the game is a little too powerful for the Steam Deck, considering that it lags quite a bit as I add NPCs and various items. That said, some Workshop mods can, and will, cause problems if you don't install everything required or remove conflicting mods first. Even so, you may want to try out a mod in a clean environment first before utilizing it in your game, and always pay attention to the ratings (if it gets negative ratings, it's probably not worth downloading).

[b]Blood.[/b] I get it. It's a war sim... but still. I would like to turn off ALL blood effects. Now, I [i]did[/i] run across a series of commands that you can input as launch options, which minimizes it some, but after a time, it seems to "break", and even characters that shouldn't bleed start pooling blood when they fall over and "die". While there's not much gore to begin with (unless you have things like zombies), it's still pretty irksome and disturbing to see your characters bleed. I also would never install mods for more gratuitous violence!

[i]UPDATE 01/28/2024:[/i] There is a [url=https://steamcommunity.com/sharedfiles/filedetails/?id=256397014&searchtext=no+blood]No Blood Mod[/url] developed by S34N that I highly recommend that remedies this. It basically replaces all blood effects with transparent textures, and it [i]should[/i] work in multiplayer sessions (though I have yet to test this extensively).

[b]Sexual content.[/b] This is more my gripe with some developers of mods than it is with the game itself. With some mods for this game, it's not made quite clear if someone injected a penis or something lewd like that in with a collection of items, or tacked it to a particular character. IMHO, it should be made clearer what is NSFW and what isn't. While there are risque characters added to the game (Shantae, for instance), if there's no exposure of buttocks, nipples, or genitals, it should be fine, but occasionally, some - *ahem!* [i]Persons[/i] - make a mod which can include these things. I, personally, am not offended by nude models, since those can be used as a basis for creating others that have clothes, hair, jewelry, etc., but I am disgusted with mods featuring genitalia or explicit sex. These should be properly tagged, but for now, the way to avoid such is to know what the developers make. If it's tagged "safe for work", or they commonly create clean content, it's likely legit and safe.

[h1]In Conclusion[/h1]
The community can make or break a game, and if you open a game up for community content, you've pretty much got a winner. Garry's Mod is a lot of fun, but it's definitely geared more for adults. I'm glad I waited until now to get it, as I might not have handled it properly early on.

Tom Clancy's Mod is a return to form in some regards but also lacks the punch many of us have come to expect from his genre defining games. Tom's Mods has its highs and lows however, there just isn't enough content here to sustain any long term enjoyment. I found myself getting bored around the 5434 hour mark and that just isn't enough in this day and age to keep me coming back.

I hear the endgame content gets good, but it takes around 10,000 hours to get to that point. Also this game suffers from not having any microtransaction or battle passes. All in all this game is a short burst of fun and I could only recommend picking it up once it goes on sale.

Final Verdict: 4.7/10

I am a 55 year old biker and trucker father, and probably one of the oldest people playing this game. I am a single father to my Son, who is 15 now. My son got this game for from his uncle, so we installed it on his computer and he started playing. By the end of the week he had 12 hours on this game. This was horrible for me, as it was already hard for me to find ways to spend time with my son, as he is always out with his friends or just watching YouTube. So i decided to make a Steam account and get this game to see if I could maybe play alongside him. I loaded into the game and started playing but I was stuck on what you where supposed to do. I asked my Son for help and he let me borrow his controller. Me and my son then played in turns and I loved it as it was the best time I had spent with my Son since my wife had died. This game has ever since brought me and my son closer again and now we actually spend time together outside the house together as well. This game reminded me that there's fun to be had in everything, and it has brought both me and my son many happy memories.

As someone with over 5,000 hours dedicated to this game, there are SEVERAL things that need to be pointed out about this game.
Both good and bad.
---------
GOOD
---------
1. There are countless amounts of mods and addons that have been created ranging from, kids in the room who just saved a weird scenario, to professional modders and map creators. Which helps to create one of the most diverse and exciting steam communities i think I've ever seen.
2. When playing with friends, i can say from experience that this game is so much fun that we were able to play for about 5-9 hours straight, just messing around with the different game modes.
3. Talking about game modes, if i had to list the amount of game modes available to people who play with friends or randoms, you would have to scroll down for hours on end.
4. This game allows you to let all of imaginations run wild as different tools at your disposal provides you with the means to create weird scenarios or amazing combat experiences on maps created by other users. 
5. Many say that playing by your self is very boring, however, what they don't remember is that this game removes that limit that most games enforce onto you. You want to spawn with hundreds upon hundreds of community made weapons from the games you love where you can do whatever you like? you can do that in gmod. do you want to make a military installation and have waves and waves of infected zombies surround your building as you try to hold them off? you can definitely do that here.
6. Lastly, some people talk about glitches that occur in this game. This is only the case because they didn't bother to read the description of the mods that they are downloading from steam which will, most of the time, describe clearly any issues or conflicting mods. When it doesn't state that, they don't bother trying to find out whats happening before complaining about it.

------
Bad
------
1. Obviously any game will have its limitation in what its graphics will be. Especially due to the fact that this game has unlimited potential, so if you're not willing to download mods for it, the graphics can be rather basic and potato
2. Also, like any public game, there is room for those who are very toxic players who want nothing more than to spread hatred and annoyance to other players. Which, can be very, very annoying to some individuals.
3. FYI, an additional note included with (1.), in the base game settings there have very little of choices to improve the graphics with any real difference.
4. The maps provided in the base games are very basic. The two which are given to you with no addons serve completely different goals. 1. A very small map with three towers, a building and a lake. 2. A massive flat grass with one huge platform in the center with nothing else. Very basic after a while. So if you want more diversity in gameplay, download community maps for a real experience.
5. Lastly, there can be quite a few addons which require games that need to be bought with money, to run.

But to conclude, this game has so many benefits which completely out-way the negatives and I would highly recommend this game for endless fun with you, and your friends.
